Date: Sat, 5 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Agrarisch Dagblad, 3 Apr 2003 [translated and edited by Mod.AS]
<http://www.agrarischdagblad.nl/pages/index.asp>

Pigs in mixed farms to be tested for fowl plague
------------------------------------------------
Pigs present on farms where poultry got infected with fowl plague (Highly
Pathogenic Avian Influenza, HPAI) are also to be tested. Animal owners are
obliged by law to cooperate. This has been announced by the Ministry of
Agriculture on Thursday. Untested pigs will not be allowed to remain in
mixed farms where poultry got infected. The ministry wants to know whether
the AI virus is, or may be, spread through pigs.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The measures announced by the Dutch Ministry of Agriculture, including
movement restrictions on ungulates from infected premises, are almost
draconian but should be evaluated in view of the deterioration of the HPAI
situation there. According to today's information by the Ministry, 177
premises, including 168 poultry farms and 9 "pet avian premises," have been
found definitely infected since the beginning of the epizootic, 5 weeks
ago. 28 additional outbreaks -- including 5 on "pet avian premises" -- are
currently "seriously suspected." So far, 9.7 million HPAI-susceptible
poultry have been culled. - Mod.AS]
